Title: The Tug of War
Source: V4
Act: II

===

~ The Alderman and Kestrel pull Fleur toward the coronation from opposite directions. The demon grows. Fleur walks in with her eyes open.

The Alderman begins to groom Fleur for the coronation. He dresses the spectacle in prophecy — public appearances, ceremonies, the careful framing of Fleur as the Solar Queen. He is building a symbol, not training a soldier. He does not fully understand what the demon is. He needs a Chosen One to crown, and Fleur is young enough and desperate enough to play the part.

Kestrel continues to advise Fleur from behind bars. She positions herself as the counterweight to the Alderman — the only person in Fleur's life who tells her the truth. But Kestrel's truth is selective. She warns Fleur about the Alderman's manipulation while steering her toward the demon. She frames the coronation as an opportunity: if Fleur can demonstrate the fire in front of the entire city, the Alderman's power collapses. The people will see the prophecy for what it is. Everything Silas suffered for will mean something.

The demon grows. Each time Fleur calls on his power — to impress the Alderman, to prove herself to Kestrel, to feel less afraid — the lantern burns hotter. Small fires flare unbidden in the city. Candles ignite without being lit. Hearths that should have cooled stay hot through the night. The cost of a dozen small surrenders is accumulating, and Fleur cannot see it because every shortcut felt reasonable at the time.

The tug of war between the Alderman and Kestrel intensifies. The Alderman wants a puppet who will crown his prophecy. Kestrel wants a weapon who will destroy it. The demon wants to be released. And Fleur, at the centre, believes she can save the community she built when she first arrived — the people she helped honestly, before the shortcuts began. She walks into the coronation because she chooses to. She has been manipulated by every side, but the choice is hers.

The Alderman presents Fleur before the assembled city as the Solar Queen. The demon surges — he has been building toward this moment. Fleur loses control. The fire spreads beyond anything she can contain. The city burns. The community Fleur built through honest work — the people who trusted her because she showed up — are in the fire. The prophecy is revealed as hollow. There is no gift. There is no Chosen One. There is only destruction, and Fleur put it there.
